1. cs.GT (Game Theory): The paper is primarily focused on developing a new representation and decomposition framework for finite games in strategic form. This is a core topic in game theory, making cs.GT the most likely sub-category.
2. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms): The paper involves the development of a new representation and decomposition framework, which may involve the use of algorithms and data structures. This makes cs.DS a likely sub-category.
3. cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence): The paper discusses equilibrium properties of potential and harmonic games, which are important concepts in AI and multi-agent systems. This makes cs.AI a likely sub-category.
4. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks): The paper may be relevant to the study of social networks and their dynamics, as games are often used to model interactions between individuals in social networks. This makes cs.SI a possible sub-category.
5. cs.LG (Machine Learning): The paper may be relevant to the study of machine learning, as games are often used to model interactions between agents in reinforcement learning settings. This makes cs.LG a possible sub-category.
